			<h3>Comparatives and Superlatives</h3>
			<p>Comparatives and Superlatives remain similar to modern English with comparatives containing an
				'<strong>r</strong>' after the stem but before the suffix, and superlatives gaining the suffix
				'<strong>-ost</strong>'.
				For example, '<em>heardra - harder</em>' and '<em>heardost - hardest</em>'. Examine the sentences,
				'<em>he wæs æðelra on his mode - he was nobler in his mind</em>' and '<em>he wæs manna wisost - he was
					wisest of men</em>'.</p>
